# Chapter 05 — Ethical Hacking Methodology

**Written by Anji | Hyderabad, India**
**Level — Beginner | Reading time — 18 minutes**

---

Every penetration tester follows a methodology. Not because someone wrote rules and forced them to, but because a structured approach is the only way to work thoroughly and professionally. Without a methodology, you miss things. You skip steps. You get distracted by interesting findings and forget to document them properly.

This chapter explains the five phases of ethical hacking — the mental framework that every professional penetration tester uses, whether they are testing a large bank in Mumbai or a small startup in Hyderabad. Understanding this framework turns a collection of tools into a coherent process.

Before anything else — one rule that applies to every single phase described in this chapter. You must have written permission before testing any system you do not personally own. Not verbal permission. Not implied permission. Written permission, clearly stating what you are authorised to test, what you are not, and during what time window. Without this, everything in this chapter is illegal under the Information Technology Act, 2000. With it, you are doing exactly what organisations pay professionals to do.

---

## The Five Phases

### Phase 1 — Reconnaissance

Reconnaissance means gathering information about your target before you touch it with any scanning tool. The goal is to learn as much as possible using only publicly available information, leaving no trace on the target's systems.

This is called passive reconnaissance. You are not sending a single packet to the target. You are reading what is already publicly visible.

What can you find through passive reconnaissance?

**WHOIS records** tell you who registered a domain, when, and sometimes contact information. Run `whois target.com` in your terminal or visit https://who.is.

**DNS records** reveal the structure of a network. The `dig` command is your tool here. `dig target.com ANY` returns all DNS records — A records pointing to IP addresses, MX records showing mail servers, NS records showing name servers. Each one tells you something about the target's infrastructure.

**Google Dorking** uses advanced Google search operators to find things that were accidentally made public. `site:target.com filetype:pdf` finds all PDFs on a domain. `site:target.com inurl:admin` looks for admin pages. `site:target.com "password"` sometimes finds configuration files or documentation that should never have been indexed. The Google Hacking Database at https://www.exploit-db.com/google-hacking-database is a collection of useful dorks.

**Shodan** at https://www.shodan.io is a search engine for internet-connected devices. Instead of searching web content, it searches for open ports and services. You can find web servers, cameras, routers, and industrial systems exposed to the internet, often running outdated software with known vulnerabilities. A free account gives you basic search access.

**LinkedIn and social media** reveal employee names, job titles, technologies used, and sometimes direct email formats. Knowing that a company uses a specific HR software or that their developers post about a particular framework is useful intelligence.

**theHarvester** is a Kali tool that automates much of this. It collects email addresses, names, subdomains, IPs, and URLs from public sources. Run `theHarvester -d target.com -b google` to gather information from Google about a domain.

The discipline of passive reconnaissance is taking time to really understand your target before you make noise. Professionals spend significant time here. Beginners skip it and go straight to scanning. That difference shows in the quality of their work.

