### Phase 3 — Gaining Access (Exploitation)

This is the phase that most beginners fixate on. In reality, it is often the most straightforward phase if the previous two were done thoroughly. By the time you reach here, you know exactly what is running and what known vulnerabilities exist. Exploitation is often a matter of matching what you found to a known technique.

This phase is where Metasploit comes in, as discussed in Chapter 04. You find a service running a vulnerable version, locate the matching Metasploit module, configure it with the target details, and run it.

But not all exploitation is automated.

**Default credentials** are embarrassingly common in real environments. Many organisations install devices and never change the default username and password. A quick check against a list of known defaults — or using Hydra from Chapter 04 against a login page — reveals these. Routers, printers, IP cameras, and admin panels are frequent offenders.

**Weak web application security** is the most common path into modern systems. SQL injection, cross-site scripting, broken authentication, insecure file uploads — these are the vulnerabilities that Chapter 06 covers in depth.

**Unpatched software** is the bread and butter of exploitation. When a vulnerability is discovered in a piece of software and a patch is released, organisations that have not applied that patch remain vulnerable. This is why update management matters enormously.

One important concept: **proof of concept, not damage**. In ethical hacking, once you have demonstrated that a vulnerability is exploitable — you have gained access, shown you can execute a command, confirmed the vulnerability is real — you stop. You do not read private data. You do not modify anything. You do not escalate further than needed to demonstrate the risk. You document what you found and move on.

This is the line between a penetration tester and an attacker.

