## Bug Bounty Programmes

If you do not yet have clients, bug bounty programmes let you practice on real systems legally and get paid when you find valid vulnerabilities.

Companies publish programmes explicitly defining which systems you may test, what vulnerability types they accept, and payment amounts. Critical findings can pay lakhs of rupees.

**HackerOne** at https://hackerone.com and **Bugcrowd** at https://bugcrowd.com are the two largest platforms. Start with programmes that have large scopes — more assets means more opportunities. Begin with low-hanging fruit: information disclosure, misconfigured headers, exposed sensitive files.

Read disclosed reports from other researchers on HackerOne to understand what real findings look like and how they are written. This is some of the best free education available.

---

## Capture the Flag Competitions

CTFs are competitions where you solve hacking challenges to find hidden flags — strings of text proving you completed a challenge.

**PicoCTF** at https://picoctf.org is the best starting point for complete beginners. **CTFtime** at https://ctftime.org lists upcoming competitions worldwide. **TryHackMe** rooms are essentially guided CTF challenges with hints — start there before competitive CTFs.

When stuck, look for writeups — blog posts where participants explain their solutions. Reading how someone solved a problem you could not is one of the best ways to learn.

